\begin_layout Subsection
The Particle-Flow Algorithm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The particle-flow (PF) algorithm aims to precisely identify particle types
 and their momenta by exploiting all detector sub systems.
 It creates particle hypotheses within an event by combining information
 from charged-particle tracks, calorimetry hits and muon tracks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The algorithm starts with the tracker information by single out first tracks
 with very tight criteria originating closely from the IP.
 On the remaining tracks, iteratively looser criteria are applied for selection.
 In the calorimeters, hits are clustered.
 This is performed by finding cells with high energy maxima (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cluster seeds
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 Then, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

topological clusters
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are constructed by combining with adjacent cells which are over a certain
 energy threshold.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One expects, that a particle causes a charged-particle track and/or hits
 several calorimeter clusters as well as one or none track in the muon system.
 All this information are linked to reconstruct each single observed particle
 while possible double counting has to be taken care of.
 The particle flow algorithm is also independent of the event complexity.
 It depends mainly on the granularity of the particle building blocks 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "particleflow"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
