\begin_layout Subsection
Missing Transversal Energy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After the particle-flow reconstruction the missing transversal energy can
 be calculated.
 Due to conversation of momentum, the net transversal momentum has to be
 zero after a collision.
 Therefore by summing up all reconstructed particles and mirroring the azimuthal
 momentum two-vector one obtains the missing transversal energy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Depending on the physics analysis, the missing transversal energy is often
 used to construct hypotheses about not directly measurable particles, like
 neutrinos or SUSY particles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Jet Definition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A jet is a group of particles originating from hadronization of gluons or
 quarks.
 Jet algorithms are used to group reconstructed particles to jets.
 By summing up the momenta within a jet, an inference about the hadronized
 parton momentum can be made.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Nowadays, the main used jet algorithms are the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{k_{T}}$
\end_inset

, the anti-
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{k_{T}}$
\end_inset

 and the Seedless Infrared-Safe Cone (SIS-Cone) algorithms 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "antiKT,siscone"

\end_inset

.
 Each is considered infrared and collinear safe.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Jet-definition"

\end_inset

 shows exemplary scenarios to explain this two necessary safety features.
\end_layout

