 case.
 Here, jet algorithms should not change their results, if one particle with
 high momentum is splitted into many collinear particles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the reconstruction by CMS, the anti-
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{k_{T}}$
\end_inset

 algorithm is used.
 Its core procedure is the iteratively calculation of the distances
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
d_{ij} & =\min\left(\frac{1}{p_{\mathrm{T,}\, i}^{2}},\,\frac{1}{p_{\mathrm{T,}\, j}^{2}}\right)\cdot\frac{\sqrt{\Delta\eta^{2}+\Delta\phi^{2}}}{R^{2}}\\
d_{i} & =\frac{1}{p_{\mathrm{T,}\, i}^{2}}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
between all proto-jets 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 Proto-jets are initially the reconstructed particles.
 After the first calculation of the two distances, a proto-jet 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is considered as a jet if 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}<d_{ij}$
\end_inset

.
 This jet is then removed from the next iteration.
 In the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}>d_{ij}$
\end_inset

 the two proto-jets 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 are merged to a new proto-jet.
 The algorithm continues until all proto-jets have been considered as jets.
 Hereby, the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $R=0.3$
\end_inset

 controls the cone sizes of the resulting jets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Identification of Jet from b-Quarks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Jet algorithms can not determine the original flavor of a hadronized quark.
 However, the relatively long decay time of B hadrons can be exploited for
 identifying jets which originate from bottom quarks.
 In a proton-proton collision, the hard interaction is often boosted against
 the lab frame.
 If a long-lived particle such as a B hadron is produced, it will fly a
 measurable distance away from the primary interaction vertex before decaying.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reconstruction by CMS uses amongst others the track counting method.
 A 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

b-tag
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 discriminator is constructed by using the significance that the n-th good
 track of a jet is not from the primary vertex 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "btagging"

\end_inset

.
 The analysis in this thesis uses the Track Counting High Purity (TCHP)
 algorithm which is based on the significance of the third track of a jet.
\end_layout

