\begin_layout Paragraph*
Projective likelihood estimator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each event in the evaluation, the Likelihood ratio
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{\mathrm{L}}(i)=\frac{\mathrm{L_{S}}(i)}{\mathrm{L_{S}}(i)+\mathrm{L_{B}}(i)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is defined.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{L_{S(B)}}$
\end_inset

 is the product propability over all input variables from the training,
 that the event is signal- (background-) like.
 The resulting classifier ranges from 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 (= background-like) to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 (= signal-like).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This method has been chosen because it is not sensitive to correlations
 within the input variables.
 This is required to do not artificially alter the signal shape if cutted
 on the classifier.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Boosted Decision Tree (BDT)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A decision tree tries to identify signal- or background-like phase spaces
 within the n-dimensional input variables space.
 This is performed by cutting sequentially on every variable to select a
 signal enhanced region.
 But a single trained decision tree can be very unstable due to statistical
 fluctuations in the training samples.
 Therefore, many decision trees are constructed.
 A stabilzed discriminator is derived by a majority vote over all trees.
 Boosting increases the discriminator stability by applying additionally
 weight factors for each decision tree based on its performance.
 The Boosted Decision Tree (BDT) discriminator can be written as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y(\vec{x})=\frac{1}{N_{\mathrm{trees}}}\cdot\sum_{j}^{N_{\mathrm{trees}}}\ln\left(\alpha_{j}\right)\cdot h_{j}(\vec{x}),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{\mathrm{trees}}$
\end_inset

 counts the number of decision trees.
 The decision result of an individual tree is 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{j}$
\end_inset

 for an event 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 which takes the values 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{j}=1$
\end_inset

 for signal-like and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{j}=-1$
\end_inset

 for background-like events.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{j}$
\end_inset

 notes the additional boosting weight.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The used 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
name{AdaBoost}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 algorithm, caculates the weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{j}$
\end_inset

 from the misclassifcation rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{err}$
\end_inset

 by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\alpha=\frac{1-\mathrm{err}}{\mathrm{err}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Through the normalization to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum\alpha_{j}=\mathrm{const.}$
\end_inset

 the BDT discriminator ranges between 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
